    value: 濯
english:
  title: A Letter Bidding Farewell to My Peer Noh Saeng Returning to His Fields
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In those early days when you and I studied together, wandering through the same paths of learning, we shared one dream—to wash our caps in fragrant waters, to set our reins loose upon the clouds of fortune, and to awaken the aspirations of a lifetime. Though I myself have not traveled far, I wear the noble crown and scarlet robes of office, content enough in my station as deputy minister. Yet you, blessed with such keen talent, have grasped no official rank. Instead, you sought out fertile fields and led your family southward. In that moment, I could not help but feel a pang—was it not admirable, yet also sorrowful?

    But as I have served in office and moved through the ranks, I have found little joy, scant pleasure in bureaucratic life. Only then did I truly revere your courage in departing. Many times I have faced south and bowed deeply in your honor.

    Now you have returned, treading once more upon the streets of the capital. I confess I suspected you harbored lingering ambitions, that you meant to pursue office again. Yet within mere days, you came to bid me farewell. In that moment, I deeply regretted my shallow judgment of you, and again I bowed, my forehead to the ground, in homage to your noble spirit.

    Alas, I have come to know it well—this life of rise and fall is but a single dream. One day I shall cast off my robes and smile my farewell to this dusty realm. How could I spend my years mired in ambition, never becoming a man of the blue mountains and white clouds?

    Our paths diverge; when we shall meet again remains uncertain. So raise high your cup—do not refuse, saying the wine is common. The weather is pure and clear, the birds sing sweetly. This is a day for wandering together. How can you bear to leave me and journey south?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Noh Saeng (盧生) is the addressee of this letter; the title indicates Lee Gyeong-bo is saying farewell as Noh returns to his rural estate.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Deputy minister'' (亞卿) refers to a position in the Korean court hierarchy of Lee''s time.'
  - key: ''
    value: The repeated motif of 'facing south and bowing' reflects the Confucian practice of bowing toward a respected friend or superior.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Man of the blue mountains and white clouds'' is a classical Chinese image for one who has withdrawn from worldly affairs to live as a recluse.'
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'common wine' (魯酒) alludes to a famous passage where Confucius refused to drink inferior wine; here Lee playfully inverts it to urge his friend not to refuse their farewell drink.
